</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,261,1930]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,336,1679,1705]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[343,466,1680,1705]" class="Insecta" family="Mantispidae" genus="Dicromantispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hyalina">
<emphasis box="[343,466,1680,1705]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">D. hyalina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seems to be close to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Erichson" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[713,838,1680,1705]" class="Insecta" family="Mantispidae" genus="Dicromantispa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[713,838,1680,1705]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">D. gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the hyaline membrane of the wings and the absence of the gonarcus median lobe, but is clearly separated by the color pattern, ectoprocts completely dark brown and ventromedial lobe curved.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1436,261,1930]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,338,1791,1817]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Greek 
<emphasis box="[886,963,1792,1817]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">hyalos</emphasis>
(= clear) and refers to the hyaline wing membrane.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
